post_text:
CURBSIDE MEAL PROGRAM TO BEGIN AUG. 26TH FOR SFDRCISD STUDENTS

Beginning Wednesday, August 26th at 11 a.m., SFDRCISD will offer student meals through the Curbside Meal Program. District enrolled students and parents will be able to pick up meals from any of the 7 campus curbside locations across the community. For ease of access, parents will be able to use the bus lanes at the Roberto “Bobby” Barrera Elementary STEM Magnet School, Ruben Chavira Elementary, Lamar Elementary, Garfield Elementary, North Heights Elementary, Calderon Elementary, and Dr. Lonnie Green Elementary. Curbside and walk-up window pick-up will be open Monday-Friday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m.
https://www.sfdr-cisd.org/media/13975/curbside-meal-program-to-begin-on-monday-for-sfdrcisd-students-rios-edits-2.pdf

post_text:
SFDRCISD challenges our parents and community to take the 2020 Census and shape the future of school lunch programs in our community. The 2020 Census not only determines the size of our community, but impacts the amount of federal funding we receive in order to provide free or reduced cost meals for our students every day. So take the challenge and pass the challenge along to others. It’s online method is quick and easy. It’s not too late, and it’s safe and secure.

Complete the 2020 Census here: https://2020census.gov/en.html

post_text: Governor Greg Abbott today announced that the Texas Health and Human Services Commission (HHSC) is extending the application deadline for the federal Pandemic-Electronic Benefit Transfer program (P-EBT) to July 31. Extending the deadline will help ensure eligible families have time to apply for this one-time food benefit. P-EBT is a one-time benefit of $285 per eligible child and can be used in the same way as Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) food benefits to pay for groceries. Eligible families include those with children who lost access to free or reduced-price school meals through the National School Lunch Program (NSLP) due to school closures. For questions regarding eligibility or to learn more, people may also contact the P-EBT Call Center at 833-613-6220, Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. Central Standard Time.

NASA - National Aeronautics and Space Administration was live.
May 30 at 3:00 PM ·

Watch history unfold on Saturday, May 30, as NASA and SpaceX launch astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley to the International Space Station. This mission marks the first time since the retirement of the space shuttle in 2011 that humans will fly to the space station from U.S. soil. The first launch attempt on May 27 was scrubbed due to weather.

Set a reminder to tune for joint NASA/SpaceX coverage starting at 11 a.m. EDT, with liftoff currently targeted for 3:22 p.m. EDT. 🚀

We’ve created a special space for our Class of 2020 graduates. Let’s share something memorable …

We’ve created a “Selfie Station” at the SPC especially for our Seniors and their families.

It’s a unique way of letting our graduates know how much they mean to us. We know that the Class of 2020 has accomplished much to get to this point.

They have demonstrated resiliency through adversity.

We invite you to participate by visiting the Student Performance Center (315 Griner St., Back Patio) Monday - Friday 8am-8pm.

post_text:
It’s Decision Day! The State of Texas declares May 1, 2020 to recognize Seniors and their college of intention. Today ECHS wants to recognize some of our Seniors Class of 2020 by posting their AWESOME pictures with the college they plan to attend after graduation! Students worked extremely hard all year to complete college applications and meet all the necessary requirements for admission. We are extremely proud of the initiative they took to plan and continue with their educational studies! Special thanks to Mrs. Foster and Mr. Mayfield for guiding students through the college preparation process in their college transitions class! Thank you to Mrs. Rodriguez and all ECHS staff that in one way or another influenced students to DREAM and go for it! Education = Opportunities!
#GenTX #DecisionDay2020

It’s Earth Day’s 50th anniversary! Typically, our schools would be celebrating in-person on April 22nd. This year, with the help of Schneider Electric, we are bringing Earth Day to you. Click the on the link below to access an “Earth Day At Home” packet, which provides ideas for engaging activities that can be done outdoors or at home with household items. We hope this toolkit can provide something simple and fun for our students and parents to enjoy in the safety of their home.

https://www.sfdr-cisd.org/media/13686/2020-earth-day-at-home-toolkit.pdf

The virus lives in tiny droplets in the lungs of people w/ COVID-19, even when they don’t show symptoms. We can breathe the same air as anyone within abt. 6 ft. of us. Staying farther apart from people during this time reduces the chance of breathing in the virus. #StayHomeTexas

El virus vive en gotas en los pulmones de personas con COVID-19, y a veces no tienen síntomas. Puedes respirar el mismo aire que cualquiera a 6 pies de ti. Mantente más alejado de las personas durante este tiempo para reducir la posibilidad de respirar el virus. #StayHomeTexas

Coughing & sneezing can send tiny infected droplets into the air which can be inhaled by anyone within 6 feet of us. Always cough or sneeze into a tissue or your elbow and immediately wash your hands to lessen the risk of spreading the virus. Be smart. Stay well! #StayHomeTexas

Toser y estornudar puede llevar gotas infectadas al aire, que pueden ser inhaladas por personas que estén a 6 pies de ti. Siempre tosa o estornude en pañuelos desechables o en el codo y lávese las manos para disminuir la propagación del virus. ¡Mantente sano! #StayHomeTexas

Common symptoms of #COVID19 are fever, dry cough, & shortness of breath. If you have mild symptoms, call your doctor & #StayHome. If you develop serious symptoms, such as trouble breathing, pressure in the chest, or bluish lips or face, call your doctor & seek care immediately.

Los síntomas comunes de #COVID19 son fiebre, tos seca y dificultad para respirar.Si tiene síntomas leves, llame a su médico y quedate en casa.Si desarrolla síntomas graves, como dificultad para respirar o presión en el pecho, busque atención médica de inmediato. #StayHome

Practica el distanciamiento social

Para prevenir la propagación de COVID-19 en nuestra comunidad, practique el distanciamiento social:
• Evite salir en público
• Cuando esté en público, mantenga una distancia de seis pies entre usted y los demás.
• Seguir las recomendaciones de los funcionarios locales y estatales.
Obtenga más información en https://texas.gov/covid19
# covid19 #texasfuerte #quedateencasa

Practice Social Distancing

To avoid the spread of COVID-19 in our community, practice social distancing:
• Avoid going out in public
• When in public, keep six feet of distance between you and others
• Follow guidance provided by local and state officials.
Get more information at https://texas.gov/covid19

Once again, SFMMS UIL demonstrated how hard work pays off at UIL State Qualifications and Regionals on Saturday, March 7, 2020 at Alamo Heights MS Meet in San Antonio. Most participants in this 2nd UIL “Texas Math and Science Coaches Association” (TMSCA) Meet were awarded 1st-10th Place Medal/Ribbon and SFMMS/DRMS received a 2nd Place Sweepstakes Trophy, as in our prior meet. Way to go, San Felipe Memorial MS!

Overall UIL State Championship Qualifiers for April 2020 - Number Sense: Ana Tarango; Calculator Applications: Alexa Muñoz, Deliamaria Vallejo, Mason Hanselman and Juan Pablo Cortez; Science: Evelyn González, Reggie Flores and Ana Tarango.

It’s about fair representation. Participate in the 2020 Census!

Every 10 years, the United States works to determine how billions of dollars are spent. It determines how much money goes to local programs – including schools, like San Felipe Del Rio CISD, new roads and emergency services. Listen to this message from Texas Senator Pete Flores (District 19).
https://youtu.be/TTRllBpJ1tk
https://youtu.be/KWVz1XGrwHU

post_text:
Shape your future. Participate in the 2020 Census!

Every 10 years, the United States works to count its residents. It is incredibly important work – it determines how the City of Del Rio and Val Verde County is represented locally and nationally; and how much money our San Felipe Del Rio school district and other important services in our community receive. Listen to this message from U.S. Representative Will Hurd (TX-23).
https://youtu.be/NVijkPwk5Yk

Ms. Scholz's class is extremely grateful and excited to be a part of FCCLA's Spreading Literacy Program. FCCLA had a book drive, where they received over two thousand books donated.
Carolina Sanchez, Vice President of FCCLA, had Ms. Scholz's students complete a reading survey and then matched each student with a book that they would enjoy reading based on their survey answers. Thank you so much to FCCLA and Carolina Sanchez for your generosity! The students love their new books!

Join us in celebrating School Board Recognition Month throughout the month of January. Stop by the administration offices at 315 Griner Street anytime Monday-Friday between 8:00am-5:00pm and snap a picture in the SFDR-CISD Spaceship!

Remember to use #SchoolBoardMonth and #SFDRCISD on Twitter and Instagram to share how you are celebrating!

Take a moment to recognize our board of trustees. Take a moment to honor the work they are doing to help your students blast off into the future. Take a moment to say thank you for the work school board members are doing on your behalf.

The SFDRCISD Board of Trustees will be recognized during the regular school board meeting on January 20th at 5:30 p.m.

SAN FELIPE DEL RIO CISD
Press Release – January 3, 2020

SFDRCISD PREPARES FOR THE 2019-2020 SECOND SEMESTER STUDENTS TO RESUME CLASSES ON WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 8TH

Happy New Year and welcome to the second semester of the 2019-2020 school year! We hope everyone has had a great winter break. Our SFDRCISD team will report to work on Monday, January 6th and 7th for a Teacher Workday and staff training in preparation for the second semester. Both elementary and secondary students will resume their regular schedule of classes beginning on Wednesday, January 8th. Secondary students are expected to report to their assigned “A Day” classes. All district and campus offices will re-open during regular business hours on Monday, January 6th.

https://bit.ly/2rWKsFm

post_text: Dom’s Angel Tree was started when a 2nd grader at North Heights Elementary had a conversation with his aunt about the importance of giving and spreading kindness. His aunt, also the Del Rio Middle School Student Council Sponsor, Ms. M. Gomez, thought, how far could his idea reach with the help of students and staff at Del Rio Middle School ? Little did they know that a small, kind gesture would bring about happiness and good cheer to 200 students at North Heights Elementary! Thank you to Trooper Santa and DPS for helping in the distribution of gifts. We thank you for bringing holiday cheer to students at North Heights Elementary! Happy holidays!

Name: Mrs. Santa Castañeda

School: Student Guidance and Learning Center

Grade Level and Subject: 6-12 ELA

Total No. of years teaching: 42

Mrs. Castañeda began her 42-year career in 1975 teaching in both Eagle Pass and Del Rio. Currently a retire/rehire teacher at the SGLC, she teaches 6-7-8th ELA, Eng. I, Eng. II, Eng. III, Eng. IV, Practical Writing, Speech and ESL. We are honored to have Mrs. Santa Castaneda as a member of the SGLC team!

post_text:
In June Natalia Ibarra represented ECHS and the state of Texas in Boston, Massachusetts at the Future Medical Leaders Conference. During her time there Natalia was able to observe surgery in real time and ask questions about the procedure. Natalia was most inspired by a speaker Carmen Blandin Tarleton.

Natalia was so motivated and inspired by this phenomenal woman that she is currently reading her story and is determined to make a difference in the world of medicine. We are proud of you young lady!Thank you for bringing one more honor to ECHS!

post_text: San Felipe Memorial Middle School and Lamar students participated in SFE-Food Service Roving Chef Program. The Roving Chef Program consists of healthy food demonstrations with Real recipes by our District Chef. The demonstration encourages participation of each student to create his or her own meal. Each student also receives a certificate of completion and a recipe card to take home to share with family and friends. Our goal is to educate students on how their school meals are prepared and how healthy food can also taste great in a fun environment! We also use the Roving Chef Program as an opportunity to expose students to new foods and recipes to expand their palate.

post_text:
In June, Jadyn Casillas represented Del Rio Freshman School and the State of Texas at the Congress of Future Medical Leaders in Boston, Massachusetts. The Congress is organized by the National Academy of Future Physicians and Medical Scientists. The Academy’s primary founding principle is to recognize and reward high achieving students dedicated to medicine or the STEM subjects.

During her time at the Congress, Jadyn watched live surgery and had a chance to question the surgeon in real time. She was also guided and mentored by prominent medical school academic leaders and some of the greatest living minds in medicine.

On September 19th, Jadyn Casillas was presented with an Award of Excellence, certifying her successful completion of the Congress.

post_text:
September 16 School Cafeteria's Line Decorating Contest

September 16 is better known as Mexican Independence Day. We thought it could be fun for staff and students to celebrate this holiday because we are in a border town with a big Hispanic community. We encouraged the cafeteria team members to decorate their cafeterias and participate in a line decorating contest. Everyone in the team made their best efforts to decorate and dress up for the occasion. The students were able to enjoy a Mexican inspired menu along with whole grain sweet bread like conchas& marranitos.
Thank you for your help in picking a winner.

Video 1 - https://bit.ly/2kUVE1w
Video 2 - https://bit.ly/2lXNTrY

post_text:
Reading Excellence and Academies Development-READ 60-Teacher Cohort Summer Reading Academy Held on July 22-26, 2019, in San Antonio, Texas

San Felipe Del Rio CISD recently sent a 60-teacher cohort comprised of English Language Arts-Reading Teachers to a summer reading academy held in San Antonio, Texas on July 22-26, 2019. The cohort of teachers spent the entire week attending professional development sessions presented by representatives from the Texas Education Agency through a state funded grant for Texas Reading Academies 2019-Reading Excellence and Academies Development (R.E.A.D.). The Reading Academy provided teachers with opportunities to enhance literacy instruction to students in kindergarten through 5th grade. The goal is to grow teachers’ knowledge, understanding, and systematic use of effective, research-based, and scientifically validated instructional methods for students. The cohort will work to promote literacy and support reading development for our students.

Please join us in working together to encourage literacy and support life-long readers in our schools.
